# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: buck-build
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:buck-build/buck-software] Buck requires the explicit declaration of dependencies.
[src:buck-build/buck-software] Because all dependencies are explicit and Buck has a directed acyclic graph of all source files and build targets, Buck can perform incremental recompilation, only rebuilding targets downstream of files that have changed.
[src:buck-build/buck-software] Buck computes a key for each target that is a hash of the contents of the files it depends on.
[src:buck-build/buck-software] It stores a mapping from that key to the build target in a build cache.
[src:buck-build/buck-software] One of the key features was the ability to share build results between multiple developers and continuous integration (CI), as Buck1 supports a HTTP Cache API.
[src:buck-build/buck-software] In 2023, Buck2 was released, claiming that builds are 2x as fast as compared to Buck1.
[src:buck-build/buck-software] One of the largest changes from Buck1 is that the core is written in Rust instead of Java, and rules are written outside the core in Starlark (the language created for the Bazel build system).
[src:buck-build/buck2-build] If you've got nothing to do, Buck2 is significantly faster.
[src:buck-build/buck2-build] If you've got lots to do, Buck2 will start doing it faster and be much closer to the critical path.
[src:buck-build/buck2-build] These restrictions apply to both the user-written `BUCK` files and the language rules.
[src:buck-build/buck2-build] Buck2 gives the right result more reliably.
[src:buck-build/buck2-build] All rules are written in Starlark, with nothing in the core of Buck2 knowing anything about languages.
[src:buck-build/buck2-build] That means that Buck2 users can define their own rules as first-class citizens.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] Build automation encompasses both sequencing build operations via non-interactive interface tools and running builds on a shared server.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] Build automation tools allow sequencing the tasks of building software via a non-interactive interface.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] A *build system* or *build automation tool* is a programming tool or set of tools that automate the compiling and linking of source code into an executable program or library.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] They streamline the software development process by managing dependencies, resolving conflicts, and ensuring consistent builds across different environments.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] When software projects grow complex, their build steps may involve multiple programming languages or compiling units, making manual build processes increasingly cumbersome.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] Dependencies between code components necessitate careful ordering and potentially different tools for each piece.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] Managing these dependencies manually can quickly lead to version conflicts, stale binaries, and difficulty tracking updates, making solutions such as shell scripts too difficult to maintain.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] While individual developers might compile code directly, a robust build system is foundational to efficient software development in large organizations and teams, where automated builds become commonplace and most builds are triggered automatically rather than manually.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] Given the essential role of build systems, it is said that they act as "repositories of essential build knowledge".
[src:buck-build/build-automation] They effectively eliminate roadblocks and accelerate development velocity by enabling engineers to share resources and results.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] An incremental build is a process within a build system where build tools use an incremental compiler to recompile only the parts of a software project that have changed since the last build, rather than rebuilding everything from scratch.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] This optimization reduces build time by leveraging dependency tracking, caching, and selective compilation.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] Incremental builds are especially valuable in large-scale software projects, where recompiling the entire codebase can be time-consuming and resource-intensive.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] By identifying and compiling only the modified components—such as source files, libraries, or modules—the build system ensures faster iteration cycles, enabling developers to test and debug changes more efficiently.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] The process relies on a dependency graph, which maps relationships between files, modules, or components in the project.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] When a change is detected, the build system traverses this graph to determine which parts of the project are affected and need to be recompiled.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] Modern build tools, such as Make, Gradle and Bazel, often incorporate incremental build capabilities to streamline development workflows.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] While incremental builds offer significant performance advantages, they also introduce challenges, such as ensuring the accuracy of dependency tracking and avoiding stale or inconsistent build artifacts.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] To address these issues, some build systems provide mechanisms for "clean builds," which rebuild the entire project from scratch to guarantee correctness when necessary.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] Because of this issue, incremental builds are rarely used in continuous integration systems, where correctness is preferred to compilation speed.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] Tools such as Make can be used via custom configuration file or using the command-line.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] Custom tools such as shell scripts can also be used, although they become increasingly cumbersome as the codebase grows more complex.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] Some tools, such as shell scripts, are task-oriented declarative programming.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] They encode sequences of commands to perform with usually minimal conditional logic.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] Some tools, such as Make are product-oriented.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] They build a product, a.k.a. target, based on configured dependencies.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] A build server is a server setup to run builds.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] In contrast to a personal computer, a server allows for a more consistent and available build environment.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] Traditionally, a build server was a local computer dedicated as a shared resource instead of used as a personal computer.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] Today, there are many cloud computing, software as a service (SaaS) websites for building.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] A continuous integration server is a build server that is setup to build in a relatively frequent way, often on each code commit.
[src:buck-build/build-automation] A build server may also be incorporated into a tool for application release automation (ARA) or application lifecycle management (ALM).
[src:buck-build/build-automation] Automating the build process is a required step for implementing continuous integration and continuous delivery (CI/CD), all of which are considered best practices for software development.
