[src:buck-build/incremental-build-model] The **incremental build model** is a method of software development where the product is designed, implemented, and tested incrementally (a little more is added each time) until the product is finished.
[src:buck-build/incremental-build-model] It involves both development and maintenance.
[src:buck-build/incremental-build-model] The product is defined as finished when it satisfies all of its requirements.
[src:buck-build/incremental-build-model] This model combines the elements of the waterfall model with the iterative philosophy of prototyping.
[src:buck-build/incremental-build-model] The product is decomposed into several components, each of which is designed and built separately (termed as builds).
[src:buck-build/incremental-build-model] Each component is delivered to the client when it is complete.
[src:buck-build/incremental-build-model] This allows partial use of the product and avoids a long development time.
[src:buck-build/incremental-build-model] It also avoids a large initial capital outlay and subsequent long waiting periods.
[src:buck-build/incremental-build-model] This model of development also helps ease the traumatic effect of introducing an all-new system all at once.
[src:buck-build/incremental-build-model] The incremental model applies the waterfall model incrementally.
[src:buck-build/incremental-build-model] The series of releases is referred to as “increments," with each increment providing more functionality to the customers.
[src:buck-build/incremental-build-model] After the first increment, a core product is delivered, which can already be used by the customer.
[src:buck-build/incremental-build-model] Based on customer feedback, a plan is developed for the next increments, and modifications are made accordingly.
[src:buck-build/incremental-build-model] This process continues, with increments being delivered until the complete product is delivered.
[src:buck-build/incremental-build-model] The incremental philosophy is also used in the agile process model (see agile modeling).
[src:buck-build/incremental-build-model] The Incremental model can be applied to DevOps.
[src:buck-build/incremental-build-model] DevOps centers around the idea of minimizing the risk and cost of a DevOps adoption whilst building the necessary in-house skillset and momentum.
[src:buck-build/incremental-build-model] Partial systems are built to produce the final system.
[src:buck-build/incremental-build-model] First tackled the highest priority requirements.
[src:buck-build/incremental-build-model] The requirement of a portion is frozen once the incremented portion is developed.
[src:buck-build/incremental-build-model] It is generally easier to test and debug than other methods of software development because relatively smaller changes are made during each iteration.
[src:buck-build/incremental-build-model] This allows for more targeted and rigorous testing of each element within the overall product.
[src:buck-build/incremental-build-model] Customers can respond to features and review the product for any needed or useful changes.
[src:buck-build/incremental-build-model] Initial product delivery is faster and costs less.
[src:buck-build/incremental-build-model] Planning: required as many people (software teams) to work on the same project but with different functions at the same time.
[src:buck-build/incremental-build-model] Modeling: involves business modeling, data modeling, and process modeling.
[src:buck-build/incremental-build-model] Construction: this involves the reuse of software components and automatic code.
[src:buck-build/incremental-build-model] Deployment: integration of all the increments.
[src:buck-build/page] Welcome to Buck2, a large scale, fast, reliable, and extensible build tool developed and used by Meta.
[src:buck-build/page] Buck2 supports a variety of languages on many platforms.
[src:buck-build/page] Starlark, which is a deterministic, immutable dialect of Python, is used to extend the Buck2 build system, enabling Buck2 to be language-agnostic.
[src:buck-build/page] With Starlark, users can define their own custom rules.
[src:buck-build/page] Buck2 multi-language support includes C++, Python, Java, Kotlin, Go, Rust, Erlang, OCaml, and more.
[src:buck-build/page] The following sub-sections contain a list of links to key points in the Buck2 Documentation website that explain the advantages of using Buck2 for you and your team.
[src:buck-build/page] Feel free to send a PR adding your project.
